@GiudGiud Unfortunately, there isn't much to do for debugging Peacock, the segmentation faults come from the C++ libraries that are per-compiled and accesses via python APIs. Typically these problems are from VTK or Qt. I debug them by finding a way to reproduce and tracing through the steps that lead to the failure, either using python debugger or print statements. As such, it will be difficult for us to debug this problem.
Depending how you installed things there might be a change that the you are running with one python (e.g., system python) but the bindings external libraries (VTK, Qt) were built with another (i.e., conda). Given the mention of the Exodus file, I am guessing the problem is coming from VTK.
To see if you can isolate the problem can you try running this script (https://itk.org/Wiki/VTK/Examples/Python/ExodusII/Read). Be sure to change the Exodus filename and variable name to something that exists, perhaps that you have opened in Paraview.
